name: Stephen Karlisch | Interiors Photographer
bio: Worldwide Interiors photographer based in Dallas & DC/VA (DMV). For workshops & education follow @karlisch_workshops

social_posts.post_text: One of the best parts of being a photographer is the journey. Having worked with interior designers for over 20 years I’ve got a lot to look back on, and every now and then I go down that rabbit hole and remember where I’ve come from. These images are just a sample from many years ago, some film(pre digital world which I miss more and more), some all natural light, some strobed, but all part of a life of experience that has informed and trained me to who I am today. I bring a unique skill set to each project based on my past experiences shooting a variety of projects in every condition imaginable. It’s been a wonderful journey and the next ten years can only be better.  Never stop learning, there is no substitute for time and experience.

The number one question interior photographers ASK ME is HOW TO CONTROL lighting.

Mastering light is the first step in taking control of your style, and attracting the types of clients you deserve.

Join me on January 18 & 19 in Dallas for this hands on workshop with me to learn how to overcome your stumbling blocks quickly and confidently when it comes to lighting, set up, customized gear list, photoshop and more.
Head to my site in my bio to see all the details and to sign up! Limit 10 slots.

“The creative time in photography should be spent on location making your images in camera, not on the computer. “

The biggest transformation at #kipsbaydallas showhouse I have ever seen was this garage entry back in 2021 by the talented @erinsander  I took a bit of liberty with some strobe light coming in the doorway(which was a closed garage) and replaced the view with some nice trees to fake the view. A quick detail shot for a @veranda mag shoot with the one and only @janshowers This shot could have gone three ways, I could have lit it from the right and let the background fall off into darkness(my first choice), shoot only ambient(light was blah, overcast and flat), or give it a little life with some strobe from behind to help bring to life the glass and ice in the bucket. It was an entertaining story and every other shot had a bit of ‘sun’ so I kept it consistent(easy to do with strobes). Our first @karlisch_workshops lighting workshop was a big success! We are so grateful to this eager group of serious professionals that came with an open mind and hungry for a new perspective about lighting for interiors. Stephen’s 30 years of photography knowledge chunked down into bite sized nuggets for each to walk away with new tools.  Passing along some of the techniques Stephen has perfected over the years will change the way this group looks at light and the potential of any scene they encounter for the rest of their careers.  Those who are dedicated to this complicated genre and seek to learn will thrive. We are excited to see where this takes all of them and the images they create. Interior photography is an art form, and the control and manipulation of light is our paint brush. 
Thank you to all of you for a wonderful week in Dallas!

Controlling the lighting in an interior photoshoot is the hardest part of the job. Some go to great lengths to shape the natural light and blend in photoshop, creating a unique view of a space to lift the narrative. Others use artificial lighting to tell the story. Which do you prefer and why? Is there a difference to you as a viewer? A story to be heard and seen by interior designers and interior photographers…Three years ago I got a message from a young Interior Designer in Cleveland who wanted to discuss shooting a project of his. This designer had no website, nothing on social media, and was barely out of college. I almost didn’t reply at first thinking it was just too strange, but I’m so glad I did. Tanner explained his project in vivid detail and sold me on it within a few minutes. I HAD TO SHOOT THIS. A couple years pass and I wasn’t hearing much from Tanner, so I kind of figured it just never materialized and was a pipe dream. Then it all got REAL. Really fast. Tanner pulled in Frances Bailey, the perfect interior stylist for this project, and we set a date to do this. Multiple zoom calls, shot lists, juggling a changing schedule, we finally got our sh*t together and knocked this one out of the park. I preach to young designers to put their projects in the hands of a professional creative team from the beginning. This is the best proof of that I could have hoped to share. First project for Tanner, first photoshoot, handled like a seasoned pro, and NOW published in House Beautiful. That is how you do it folks. Be like Tanner, Tanner good, he so good. What a fun and hard week it was, but so worth it in the end. Now we sleep. Thank you Tanner for reaching out to me long, long ago. I believed in you from day one. Congratulations! ✨✨

Last December I spent a few days wandering a dark, cold Paris by myself. I think it’s the best therapy for a photographer to take a solo vacation somewhere that inspires you, and just walk and observe with no plan. It was a perfect reset. While there I did manage to spend time with a dear friend, @allison.crawford who had recently moved from Austin to Paris(see her account for her amazing journey). She wanted to document her apartment, and we spent a day arranging shots, and just enjoying the process. I wish all my shoots could be this simple. No fuss, just flowing from shot to shot and taking time to laugh and appreciate what we were doing. It’s rare but when it does happen I embrace it and it is a reminder of why I do what I do. It’s not all about the house, or furnishings or art, it’s about the people that I’m surrounded by that make it all happen. Thank you Allison for inviting me to shoot that day. It was the highlight of my trip! Merci beaucoup! #parisphotographer #parisinteriors #parisinteriordesign #parisapartment #decoratelikeaparisian #frenchstyle #parisstyle #coutureinteriors #newparisinteriors

Feel free to drop your questions for Stephen! 

Published in Architectural Digest, Veranda, Elle Decor, House Beautiful to name a few, Stephen has consistently helped designers pitch stories to get published in local, regional and national publications for over 15 years.

As a former architecture student, Stephen learned how to see space in an orderly way. That education has been invaluable in his pursuit of photographing interiors. 

Stephen grew up traveling the world as the son of a Navy pilot, living in Asia, Italy, and spending his formative years in Brussels, Belgium. Studying architecture and then photography grounded him in the visual arts world, naturally progressing to focusing on interiors. Now he works with the top interior designers in Texas and throughout the US to help elevate their brand assets for coffee table books, editorial features and visual archives.

Kitchen by @moredesignbuild @kdbiel at this years Kips Bay Dallas. Two things about this shoot that I will always remember. First, you should see the ‘before’ shots of this space to appreciate the genius behind the design(I hope they are posted somewhere). Second, this was a crazy day, it was almost pitch black outside and raining really hard. It made lighting the space a challenge knowing the rain would stop and this shot would have to blend in to some ambient shots later. I enjoy these challenges the most, making the brain work while downing my quad americano on an empty stomach. 😁. Big thanks to @russellbrightwell for leaping into this one a little late. We all pitched in and got it done. Showhouses are a b*tch for many reasons, but the small miracle moments are what we are here for.

Digging through some old Dropbox folders for fun and looking at portfolio shots from over 10 yrs ago. I remember this shoot for @dhome and how annoyed the creative director was at how moody the shots were. It was at a time when light/bright/airy was all the rage. I always consider the space and the vibe I am getting from it. I loved the mood and leaving the lights on(oh no!!😱), which was such a no-no at the time. It’s fun to look back at decisions I made and how they impact the way I see and approach shoots now.
